The two Poles
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
A former leader of Solidarity, a former political prisoner, and a former minister for foreign affairs – who led Poland's accession to NATO – Geremek refused to sign another new declaration stating that he was not an agent of the secret police during communism.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the Polish government's behavior, and Geremek declared that the law on lustration [denazification] constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of stirring up anti-Polish sentiments.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuses of power.
A constitutional court decision on May 11 largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
But this law is part of a broader policy of the Polish government aimed at weakening the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first a fight for freedom, then a struggle for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul through which man expresses what is best within him, while the second unleashes the worst: envy, intrigue, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into secrecy when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in full light in 1989, in the wake of Gorbachev's "perestroika."
In the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that opened the way for the peaceful dismantling of communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than one of revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all over a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. Even the former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and market economy.
But not everyone followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revenge-seekers, post-communist provincial troublemakers, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the voice of ethnic-clerical fundamentalism.
There are worrying signs everywhere: the authority of the judiciary is being undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Court is questioned, officials are bought off, and the role of prosecutor is politicized.
Every day, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all this?
Every successful revolution has winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public liberties, but also more crime, a market economy but also the risks of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by growing income inequality.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also induced fear of foreigners and fear of an invasion of Western mass culture.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainty.
In large enterprises, workers from Solidarity became the victims of the freedoms they had won.
In the communist prison system, people were considered to belong to the state, but it took care of them.
In a world of freedom, no one takes care of us.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the existing coalition governs, combining the conservative elixir of George Bush with the centralism of Vladimir Putin.
The veterans of Solidarity thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the pinnacle.
But the communists who were at fault were not punished, and the virtuous Solidarity activists were not rewarded.
Thus, a sense of injustice gave birth to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed against both old enemies and old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was Poland's greatest achievement in 300 years.
To them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland lacked a moral revolution that would ensure crimes were not left unpunished, virtue was rewarded, and injustices were righted.
After their victory in the general elections of 2005, the political parties of the losers chose a method: a large-scale purge.
According to initial estimates, the lustration process should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the security service archives; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people scheduled for lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make false declarations must be fired and barred from practicing their profession for ten years.

Cardinal Dziwisz of Krakow reminds us that there is no room for "revenge, vengeance, lack of respect for human dignity, and baseless accusations."
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The goal of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects, whether proven or not, who had belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would neither be part of NATO nor of the European Union.
Today, two Poles face each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and revenge is fighting against the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
That Poland – one of openness and tolerance, of John Paul II and Czeslaw Milosz, of my friends from the underground and from prison – must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The decision of the Constitutional Court leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will neither destroy what gave birth to it, the desire for freedom, nor what it has produced, a democratic state.
